				<text>37.1.1.9 Morse Code</text>
		</name>
    <questiontext format="moodle_auto_format">
				<text><![CDATA[<p class="HELM_exercise">Exercise</p>
<ol class="HELM_parts">
<li> How many different signals consisting of \({@symb@}\) symbols can be sent using the dot and dash of Morse code? [[input:ans1]][[validation:ans1]][[feedback:prt1]]</li>
<li> How many can be sent if {@symb@} symbols <span><em>or less</em></span> can be sent? [[input:ans2]][[validation:ans2]][[feedback:prt2]]
</li></ol>]]></text>
		</questiontext>
    <generalfeedback format="moodle_auto_format">
				<text><![CDATA[<h4 class="HELM_solution">Solution</h4>
<ol class="HELM_parts">
    <li>Clearly, the order of the symbols is important. We can choose each symbol in two ways, either a dot or a dash. The number of distinct signals is
        <br>\(\qquad 2\times \cdots \times 2= 2^{@symb@}={@ta1@}\).</li>
    <li>If {@symb@} <span><em>or less</em></span> symbols may be used, the total number of signals may be calculated as follows:
        <br>Using one symbol \(2^1 = 2\) ways
        <br> Using two symbols:\(2\times 2= 2^2=4\) ways
        <br>...<br>Using {@symb@} symbols:\(2^{@symb@}={@ta1@}\) ways
        <br>The total number of signals which may be sent is: \[\sum_{n=1}^{@symb@} 2^n = 2^1 + 2^2 + \cdots + 2^{@symb@} = {@ta2@}.\]</li>
</ol>]]></text>
		</generalfeedback>
